      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm trying to figure out how to calculate our inventory turnover ratio for my clothing shop. what's the formula for that and what does it actually tell me if the number is low?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The inventory turnover ratio is calculated by dividing your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) by your average inventory. A low number means you are selling your clothes slowly, which is a good sign for a boutique that needs to keep its stock fresh and avoid dead stock, but a bad sign if you are losing money on unsold items. It tells you how many times you sell through your entire inventory in a given period, so a low number indicates that your current stock sits on the shelf too long.",
